      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Why This Gap Exists — Chemistry Context\n\nThis absence is chemically understandable for several reasons:\n\n1. **Non-aqueous preference:** Uranyl–crown ether complexes (e.g., UO₂²⁺ + 18-crown-6) are predominantly studied in **organic solvents** (acetonitrile, propylene carbonate) or in **liquid–liquid extraction** systems, not in aqueous solution. SRD-46 focuses on aqueous equilibria.\n\n2. **Geometry mismatch:** The linear O=U=O oxo groups of uranyl occupy axial positions, leaving the equatorial belt for ligand coordination. Crown ethers bind equatorially, but the large ionic radius of UO₂²⁺ and its high charge density make aqueous crown complexes thermodynamically marginal compared to competing hydration.\n\n3. **Literature scope:** Quantitative log β values for UO₂²⁺–crown systems in water are sparse in the primary literature, and SRD-46 may not have curated them.",
